\begin_layout Title
How to compute advection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Question
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to know the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 used in the turbulence map (eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Pierrehumbert_map"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "pierrehumbert_tracer_1994"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "ngan_scalar_2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Keeping 
\begin_inset Formula $U\tau/c=0.5$
\end_inset

 as used in Young et al.
 2001 (in which the coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $c=2$
\end_inset

), we will then be able to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, which determines the rest of the parameter values.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
x(t+\tau) & =x(t+t')+U\tau/c\cos\left(ky(t+t')+\phi(t)\right)\\
y(t+\tau) & =y(t+t')+U\tau/c\cos\left(kz(t+t')+\theta(t)\right)\\
z(t+\tau) & =z(t+t')+U\tau/c\cos\left(kx(t+\tau)+\psi(t)\right)
\end{cases}\label{eq:Pierrehumbert_map}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following, we define 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 the velocity of the flow as the sum of the components of the displacement
 vector, divided by the duration of a timestep, i.e.:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{ccc}
V & = & \frac{1}{\tau}\sqrt{\left(x(t+\tau)-x(t+t')\right)^{2}+\left(y(t+\tau)-y(t+t')\right)^{2}+\left(z(t+\tau)-z(t+t')\right)^{2}}\\
\left\langle V\right\rangle  & = & \frac{1}{\tau}\sqrt{\left\langle \left(\frac{U}{c}\right)^{2}\cos^{2}\left(ky(t+t')+\phi(t)\right)+\left(\frac{U}{c}\right)^{2}\cos^{2}\left(kz(t+t')+\theta(t)\right)+\left(\frac{U}{c}\right)^{2}\cos^{2}\left(kx(t+\tau)+\psi(t)\right)\right\rangle }
\end{array}\label{eq:v_whole_formula}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this formula, we can obviously compute 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Value of V
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Usual definition of the Reynolds number
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are working at the Kolmogorov scale, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Re\approx1$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Re$
\end_inset

 is the Reynolds number.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The usual formulation of the Reynolds number is :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Re=\frac{VL_{c}}{\nu}\label{eq:re_first}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is the velocity of the flow (m/s), 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{c}$
\end_inset

 is a characteristic linear dimension and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=10^{-6}$
\end_inset

m
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

.s
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is the kinematic viscosity of the fluid.
 We first define 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{c}$
\end_inset

 as the dimension of the cube corresponding to the Kolmogorov scale.
 In the ocean, this corresponds to scales between 0.1 and 1 cm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barton_impact_2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This leads to 
\begin_inset Formula $V\approx10^{-4}$
\end_inset

 m.s
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, we can also define a length 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{v}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the equivalent sphere diameter, i.e.:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{cccc}
 & \frac{4}{3}\pi\left(\frac{L_{v}}{2}\right)^{3} & = & L_{c}^{3}\\
\Leftrightarrow & L_{v} & = & 2L_{c}\left(\frac{3}{4\pi}\right)^{1/3}\\
\Leftrightarrow & L_{v} & = & 1.24\text{ cm}
\end{array}\label{eq:re_lv}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we use 
\begin_inset Formula $V\approx\nu/L_{v)}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V\approx8.1\times10^{-5}$
\end_inset

 m.s
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
WY's proposition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When suggesting a more complex map for the turbulent flow, WY also proposed
 another way to write the Reynolds number.
 This is an adaptation of his email from June, 15
\begin_inset Formula $^{\ensuremath{\text{th}}}$
\end_inset

2021, with personal (CP) annotations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's start with a map comprising 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 wavenumbers, i.e.
 the first component (reasoning is the same for the others) of the velocity
 can be written:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{1}=\sum_{n=1}^{N}U_{n}cos[k_{n}x_{2}+\phi_{n}]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{n}=nk$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}=k=2\pi/L_{K}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{K}$
\end_inset

 being the Kolmogorov scale (
\begin_inset Formula $\approx$
\end_inset

 1 cm), and all 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{n}$
\end_inset

 are random phases.
 The mean square velocity in 2D is then 
